item.dc:creator: Comrade_Tiki
item.description:
Merriam-Webster:

Definition of ACCESSORY FRUIT[indent]: a fruit (as the apple) of which a conspicuous part consists of tissue other than that of the ripened ovary[/indent]

Definition of FRUIT

[indent]1
b (1) : the usually edible reproductive body of a seed plant; especially : one having a sweet pulp associated with the seed [/indent]

Definition of STRAWBERRY

1 : the juicy edible usually red fruit of any of several low-growing temperate herbs (genus Fragaria) of the rose family that is technically an enlarged pulpy receptacle bearing numerous achenes on its surface

(citey enough yet?)

And before you jump to definition 1d,
know that the “fruit” we’re defining is in the context of something a plant produces that is eaten - - not in the context of plant reproduction micromechanics - - and as 1d makes no mention of any relation with edibility, its specification does not apply.

item.title: nectarines are a top tier fruit.
item.dc:creator: Fnoigy
item.description:
Bolteh:

Lemons are tasty as well tbh, though I don’t eat them very often

Gotta agree here.

Also, technically speaking a strawberry is not a fruit. It’s a sugary, fleshy receptacle. The “seeds” are each a small, dry fruit.
And pumpkins are berries.
And peaches, plums, cherries, and olives are all in the same group of fruit.
And we only eat the seeds of coconuts.
Those helicopter seeds are also fruit.
Various nuts are fruits.
Never eat a wild “tomato”, because chances are it’s not a tomato, but a relative that looks like it, and is probably very very toxic, since tomatoes are in the night shade family, and are one of the only members of that family that aren’t horribly poisonous.

item.title: nectarines are a top tier fruit.
item.dc:creator: Comrade_Tiki
item.description:
Mmmmm mm, peanut butter and bananas. Bananas are a great fruit because of how subtle they are. Practically anything can be combined with bananas, and it will form an acceptable flavour.

Mr.Shadow:

That’s only too pets, who can’t peel the skin of or know you’re not supposed to eat the leafs and pit.

The meat of an avocado, guacamole thus included, is still deadly to a wide range of birds.
Furthermore, my parrot is intelligent enough to know which parts are intended to be edible, and would ignore the leaves and peel off the skin, obviously not eating its ginormous seed, if he were given the chance. But that intellect would be useless considering the poison that is avocado.

It evolved to be swallowed practically whole by giant herbivores, who have since gone extinct, and has no role in the modern day foodchain except as a novelty item paraded by gringos which is hazardous to some of the most fundamental life surrounding humans.
